ars as a team (1933-1940) as they navigated the primarily white world of amateur baseball, including their increasing resistance to racism and unfair treatment. After the team disbanded, Chatham Coloured All-Stars players in the community helped to racially integrate local baseball and supported new Black teams in the 1940s and 1950s. While exploring the history of Black baseball in one southwestern Ontario community, this book also provides insights into larger themes in Canadian Black history and sport history including gender, class, social justice, and memory and remembrance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBaseball players, BlackzOntariozChathamxHistoryy20th century. 0aBaseballzOntariozChathamxHistoryy20th century. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aSocial Science: Multiculturalism. 4aSports & Recreation. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Baseball / History.2bisacsh  aBlack baseball culture.  aBlack baseball in Canada.  aBlack community history.  aBlackness and whiteness in sport.  aclass.  aconstructions of Black masculinity.  amemory and remembrance.  asouthern Ontario.  asouthwestern Ontario.  asport and social justice.  asport in racialized communities.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112586440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771125864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771125864/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles